Agribank, Cnooc, PetroChina, Ping An: Hong Kong Stocks Preview

-- B y   K a n a   N i s h i z a w a
-- 
2011-04-28T00:43:44Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-04-27/china-minsheng-banking-cnooc-hong-kong-stocks-preview.html
The following companies may have
significant price changes in Hong Kong trading. Stock symbols
are in parentheses. Share prices are as of the last close.  The  Hang Seng Index (HSI)  fell 0.5 percent to 23,892.84. The Hang
Seng  China  Enterprises Index, which tracks so-called H shares of
Chinese companies, slid 0.8 percent to 13,452.44.  Agricultural Bank of China Ltd. (1288)  (1288 HK): The nation’s
largest lender by customers said first-quarter profit rose 36
percent to 34.1 billion yuan ($5.24 billion) as profitability of
loans and fee income increased. The stock was unchanged at
HK$4.71.  China Minsheng Banking Corp. (1988 HK): The nation’s first
non-state lender said first-quarter net income rose 45 percent
from the same period last year to 6.21 billion yuan. The stock
declined 0.4 percent to HK$7.59.  China Shipping Container Lines Co. (2866 HK): The company
reported a first-quarter net loss of 146 million yuan. The stock
fell 1.9 percent to HK$3.16.  Cnooc Ltd. (883)  (883 HK): China’s biggest offshore oil producer
said revenue rose 59 percent in the first quarter from a year
earlier after crude prices surged and production increased to
meet domestic demand. The stock slid 0.5 percent to HK$19.60.  PetroChina Co. (857 HK):  Asia ’s biggest company by market
value said first-quarter profit grew 14 percent to 37 billion
yuan. The stock declined 0.5 percent to HK$11.60.  Ping An Insurance (Group) Co. (2318 HK): China’s second-
largest insurer said first-quarter profit rose 28 percent to
5.81 billion yuan as a stock-market rally boosted investment
returns and premium income rose. The stock fell 1.1 percent to
HK$84.65.  Zijin Mining Group Co. (2899 HK): China’s largest gold
miner by market value said first-quarter net income increased 17
percent to 1.39 billion yuan. The stock fell 1.4 percent to
HK$6.35.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Kana Nishizawa in Tokyo at 
